author: @poocicle
text: YouTube Rewind's downfall can be attributed to a culmination of factors that led to its disappointing execution. Primarily, it failed to authentically represent the diverse and vibrant creator community that defines YouTube, instead opting for a formulaic, corporate-driven approach that felt disconnected from the platform's essence. By sidelining genuine moments and creators in favor of mainstream celebrities and scripted segments, it lost the essence of what made previous Rewinds engaging. Furthermore, its attempt to address controversies and trends in a sanitized manner only served to highlight its lack of understanding of the platform's culture, resulting in a product that felt out of touch and disingenuous to both creators and viewers alike.

"Youtube Rewind 2018: Everyone Controls Rewind" is a 7-minute video posted by YouTube on December 6, 2018. The video begins with the statement, "Aaah, it's rewind time," followed by a group of creators discussing what they would include in a rewind video if they had control. The creators banter and make jokes about what they want to see in the video, such as Fortnite and Marques Brownlee, and even argue about what kind of music should be played.

The video transitions into a montage of different YouTube personalities and creators, showcasing various highlights from the year, including popular trends, challenges, and memes. The creators in the video make suggestions on what they think should be included in the rewind, such as K-pop, a Royal Wedding, melting lipstick, and even a Mukbang. As the video progresses, it shifts from showcasing popular trends and memes to celebrating people who made significant contributions in various areas, such as mental health, education, Asian representation, and empowering women.

Towards the end of the video, the creators express their gratitude to their community and acknowledge the importance of support during their best and worst times. They give a moment to everyone who supported them when they got sick and acknowledge the importance of comments and messages. The creators then read and react to comments from their viewers. They also thank their viewers for being a part of their community and for supporting them throughout the year. The final line of the video is one of the creators saying, "Aaaahhh That's hot, that's hot."

Overall, "YouTube Rewind 2018: Everyone Controls Rewind" is a playful and lighthearted video that showcases the diversity and creativity of the YouTube community. The video captures the essence of the year and highlights the contributions of different people in various fields. The creators' banter and humor make the video entertaining and engaging, while their sincere moments of gratitude show their appreciation for their community. The video is a celebration of the year and a tribute to the creativity, talent, and resilience of the YouTube community.

author: @MrBradshawbenjamin
text: Give us the option to make the dislike count visible for everyone on our own videos if we want, but leave the default as them being off. This way, one can demonstrate a degree of openness about it, but you don't have to turn them on if your don't want, and it doesn't give much credibility to those who call you a coward for turning them off, since that's how they started. We will still be able to know, however, that the corporations are cowards, since they won't turn them on. Besides just them hiding the dislikes, it's almost like the corporations are hiding themselves, since now no video has the dislike count enabled. By giving us this option, we expose the corporations while still protecting the (especially small) content creators.

author: @magentamonster
text: Why does everyone say that YouTube removed dislikes? It didn't, it merely hid the dislike count. You can still dislike videos, and the uploader and Google can still see the dislike count, but no one else can. And dislikes still teach YouTube's algorithm that you don't like the content. And YouTube might then generalise that knowledge of you to other users who it sees as having similar preferences as you. Resulting in less people seeing that disliked content. But I've also heard disliking can backfire, as it is counted as an interaction.
